content:
I'm working with Jinja2 in a project and I've found out that it doesn't support multiple level template inheritance, unlike Django. Is there a way I can specify a base template, specify 3 or 4 templates based on that, and then build the main pages using those base templates in Jinja2 similar to Django? 

{% extends "foo" %} 

I'm relatively new to both Django and Jinja2 and would appreciate any guidance or information.

Jinja2 does indeed support multiple levels of template inheritance, similar to Django. The key is to understand how to properly structure your templates and use the `{% extends %}` and `{% block %}` tags effectively. Here's how you can achieve multiple level template inheritance in Jinja2:

1. **Base Template**: Create a base template that defines the overall structure and layout of your site. This template will include blocks that can be overridden by child templates.

   ```html
   <!-- base.html -->
   <!DOCTYPE html>
   <html lang="en">
   <head>
       <meta charset="UTF-8">
       <title>{% block title %}Default Title{% endblock %}</title>
   </head>
   <body>
       <header>
           {% block header %}
           <h1>Default Header</h1>
           {% endblock %}
       </header>

       <main>
           {% block content %}
           <p>Default Content</p>
           {% endblock %}
       </main>

       <footer>
           {% block footer %}
           <p>Default Footer</p>
           {% endblock %}
       </footer>
   </body>
   </html>
   ```

2. **Intermediate Template**: Create intermediate templates that extend the base template. These templates can override some blocks defined in the base template and introduce new blocks if needed.

   ```html
   <!-- intermediate.html -->
   {% extends "base.html" %}

   {% block title %}Intermediate Title{% endblock %}

   {% block header %}
   <h1>Intermediate Header</h1>
   {% endblock %}

   {% block content %}
   {% block intermediate_content %}
   <p>Intermediate Default Content</p>
   {% endblock %}
   {% endblock %}
   ```

3. **Specific Templates**: Finally, create specific templates that extend the intermediate templates. These templates can override the blocks defined in both the base and intermediate templates.

   ```html
   <!-- page.html -->
   {% extends "intermediate.html" %}

   {% block title %}Page Title{% endblock %}

   {% block intermediate_content %}
   <p>Specific Page Content</p>
   {% endblock %}
   ```

With this structure, you can build complex templates by stacking layers of inheritance. Each template level can override or extend blocks as needed, providing flexibility similar to what you might be used to in Django.

Remember to properly set up your Jinja2 environment to locate the templates directory, and ensure your template files are stored in a way that Jinja2 can find them. With this setup, you should be able to achieve the desired template inheritance and structure for your project.
